picom
picom is useful for stabilising mismatches between frame rates of media players/screens and multi monitors.
scrolling can create visual artifacts. picom corrects this
picom appears to load the cpu dependent on the resolution size or pixel demand of the secondary displays.
The larger the resolution of a secondary display, the more cpu demand
specialised mpv settings can be used to circumvent this as well as downgrading to a smaller resolution or monitor
Ideally, a machine with a dedicated gpu, and a sufficient cpu would solve these minor inefficiencies.
A more robust machine would put the current cpu usage of say 30% for background tasks (eg picom, background media video, background bufferring, daemons etc)
to maybe 10% or less. And a dedicated gpu would make this improvement more noticeable, in so far as cpu and gpu tasks would be segmented and non-interferring
